<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 10:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I295dd720630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Documentary and Demonstrative Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720da70682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:5.</label.designator><headtext>Voluminous records</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Voluminous entries in business records[<footnote.reference refid="Ic5df85307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] may become an issue in a case. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1980132836" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I55028ba27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Stewart v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic5df85317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] an expert witness was properly permitted to testify as to his examination of a large number of entries, but extracts that he had made from these entries were not admissible.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Generally, Georgia courts have allowed summaries of voluminous records into evidence when the underlying records are available for inspection.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5df85327fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1994048008" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5504d5927fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Loper v. Drury</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic5df85337fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals explained that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“a summary of business records is properly <page no="354"/>admitted on two conditions: [1] that the original records are voluminous and contain substantial amounts of irrelevant matter; and [2] that the originals are available to the court and to the parties.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic5dfac407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Code provides for the admission of summaries of voluminous documents. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-10-1006" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I55065c307fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-10-1006</cite.query> states:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>The contents of otherwise admissible voluminous writings, recordings, or photographs which cannot conveniently be examined in court may be presented in the form of a chart, summary, or calculation. <eos/><bos/>The originals, or duplicates, shall be made available for examination or copying, or both, by other parties at a reasonable time and place. <eos/><bos/>The court may order that the contents of such writings, recordings, or photographs be produced in court.<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext></para></display.quote><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>For purposes of proving money due under a defaulted loan, a bank was not allowed to use a screen shot of the balance due as evidence and submit it under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-10-1006" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I5506d1607fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-10-1006</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>A screen shot is neither a data compilation under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I5506d1617fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(6)</cite.query>, nor a summary under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-10-1006" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I5506d1627fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-10-1006</cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5dfac417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A summary of hours worked by attorneys and paralegals is inadmissible under the statute where the underlying bills have not been made available to the opposing party or the court.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5dfac427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Summaries made for the purpose of settlement negotiations were not admissible because (a) they were not made in the ordinary course of business and (b) the party trying to introduce them presented no evidence that the underlying documents were so voluminous that the summaries were necessary.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5dfac437fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic5df85307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I550216707fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(6)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5df85317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1980132836" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5502d9c27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Stewart v. State, 246 Ga. 70, 268 S.E.2d 906 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5df85327fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1991162485" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I550412427fc011ea988285db8533e975">Lawhorn v. State, 200 Ga. App. 451, 408 S.E.2d 425 (1991)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1982150424" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I550412457fc011ea988285db8533e975">Tyner v. Sheriff, 164 Ga. App. 360, 297 S.E.2d <page no="354"/>114 (1982)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>Compare <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1993202190" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I550412487fc011ea988285db8533e975">Dixieland Truck Brokers, Inc. v. International Indem. Co., 210 Ga. App. 160, 435 S.E.2d 520 (1993)</cite.query> (extracts of insurance records were not admissible where originals were not available to court).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5df85337fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1994048008" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5504fca27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Loper v. Drury, 211 Ga. App. 478, 440 S.E.2d 32 (1993)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5dfac407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="1994048008" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5505e7027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Loper v. Drury, 211 Ga. App. 478, 481, 440 S.E.2d 32 (1993)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>Also see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="2036450463" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5505e7057fc011ea988285db8533e975">Tafel v. Lion Antique Cars &amp; Investments, Inc., 297 Ga. 334, 773 S.E.2d 743 (2015)</cite.query>, where the Court upheld the trial court&apos;s exclusion of a summary of attorney&apos;s fees because the underlying records were not made available to the parties and the trial court prior to offering the summaries into evidence as required by statute.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5dfac417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="2038257924" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I55071f827fc011ea988285db8533e975">D&apos;Agnese v. Wells Fargo Bank, N.A., 335 Ga. App. 659, 782 S.E.2d 714 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5dfac427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="2036450463" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I550794b27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Tafel v. Lion Antique Cars &amp; Investments, Inc., 297 Ga. 334, 773 S.E.2d 743 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5dfac437fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="2037793104" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I550809e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Lyman v. Cellchem Intern., LLC, 335 Ga. App. 266, 779 S.E.2d 474 (2015)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017203" w-serial-number="2040811550" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I550809e57fc011ea988285db8533e975">300 Ga. 475, 796 S.E.2d 255 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="355"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 10:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
